implements UsesCustomNull
    Provides a bunch of information about a completed read, write, or notification.

      • serviceUuid

        public final java.util.UUID serviceUuid()
        The UUID of the service associated with this BleDevice.ReadWriteListener.ReadWriteEvent. This will always be a non-null UUID, even if target() is BleDevice.ReadWriteListener.Target.DESCRIPTOR. If target() is BleDevice.ReadWriteListener.Target.RSSI then this will be referentially equal (i.e. you can use == to compare) to NON_APPLICABLE_UUID.

      • charUuid

        public final java.util.UUID charUuid()
        The UUID of the characteristic associated with this BleDevice.ReadWriteListener.ReadWriteEvent. This will always be a non-null UUID, even if target() is BleDevice.ReadWriteListener.Target.DESCRIPTOR. If target() is BleDevice.ReadWriteListener.Target.RSSI then this will be referentially equal (i.e. you can use == to compare) to NON_APPLICABLE_UUID.

If target() is BleDevice.ReadWriteListener.Target.CHARACTERISTIC or BleDevice.ReadWriteListener.Target.RSSI then this will be referentially equal (i.e. you can use == to compare) to NON_APPLICABLE_UUID.

      • data

        public final byte[] data()
        The data sent to the peripheral if type() BleDevice.ReadWriteListener.Type.isWrite(), otherwise the data received from the peripheral if type() BleDevice.ReadWriteListener.Type.isRead(). This will never be null. For error cases it will be a zero-length array.

      • rssi

        public final int rssi()
        This value gets updated as a result of a BleDevice.readRssi(ReadWriteListener) call. It will always be equivalent to BleDevice.getRssi() but is included here for convenience.
        See Also:
        BleDevice.getRssi(), BleDevice.getRssiPercent(), BleDevice.getDistance()

      • mtu

        public final int mtu()
        This value gets set as a result of a BleDevice.setMtu(int, ReadWriteListener) call. The value returned will be the same as that given to BleDevice.setMtu(int, ReadWriteListener), which means it will be the same as BleDevice.getMtu() if status() equals BleDevice.ReadWriteListener.Status.SUCCESS.
        See Also:
        BleDevice.getMtu()

      • status

        public final BleDevice.ReadWriteListener.Status status()
        Indicates either success or the type of failure. Some values of BleDevice.ConnectionFailListener.Status are not used for certain values of BleDevice.ReadWriteListener.Type. For example a BleDevice.ReadWriteListener.Type.NOTIFICATION cannot fail with BleDevice.ReadWriteListener.Status.TIMED_OUT.

      • time_ota

        public final Interval time_ota()
        Time spent "over the air" - so in the native stack, processing in the peripheral's embedded software, what have you. This will always be slightly less than time_total().

      • time_total

        public final Interval time_total()
        Total time it took for the operation to complete, whether success or failure. This mainly includes time spent in the internal job queue plus time_ota(). This will always be longer than time_ota(), though usually only slightly so.

      • gattStatus

        public final int gattStatus()
        The native gatt status returned from the stack, if applicable. If the status() returned is, for example, BleDevice.ReadWriteListener.Status.NO_MATCHING_TARGET, then the operation didn't even reach the point where a gatt status is provided, in which case this member is set to BleStatuses.GATT_STATUS_NOT_APPLICABLE (value of -1). Otherwise it will be 0 for success or greater than 0 when there's an issue. Generally this value will only be meaningful when status() is BleDevice.ReadWriteListener.Status.SUCCESS or BleDevice.ReadWriteListener.Status.REMOTE_GATT_FAILURE. There are also some cases where this will be 0 for success but status() is for example BleDevice.ReadWriteListener.Status.NULL_DATA - in other words the underlying stack deemed the operation a success but SweetBlue disagreed. For this reason it's recommended to treat this value as a debugging tool and use status() for actual application logic if possible.

        See BluetoothGatt for its static GATT_* status code members. Also see the source code of BleStatuses for SweetBlue's more comprehensive internal reference list of gatt status values. This list may not be totally accurate or up-to-date, nor may it match GATT_ values used by the bluetooth stack on your phone.

      • solicited

        public final boolean solicited()
        This returns true if this event was the result of an explicit call through SweetBlue, e.g. through BleDevice.read(UUID), BleDevice.write(UUID, byte[]), etc. It will return false otherwise, which can happen if for example you use BleDevice.getNativeGatt() to bypass SweetBlue for whatever reason. Another theoretical case is if you make an explicit call through SweetBlue, then you get BleDevice.ReadWriteListener.Status.TIMED_OUT, but then the native stack eventually *does* come back with something - this has never been observed, but it is possible.

      • connectionPriority

        public final BleConnectionPriority connectionPriority()
        This value gets set as a result of a BleDevice.setConnectionPriority(BleConnectionPriority, ReadWriteListener) call. The value returned will be the same as that given to BleDevice.setConnectionPriority(BleConnectionPriority, ReadWriteListener), which means it will be the same as BleDevice.getConnectionPriority() if status() equals BleDevice.ReadWriteListener.Status.SUCCESS.
        See Also:
        BleDevice.getConnectionPriority()
